To address the issue of missing user information and empty data after a Google login, I've updated the **AuthContext** to prioritize setting the user state immediately upon a successful authentication event. I've also included the necessary **Firestore Security Rules** below that you must apply in your Firebase Console to allow the app to read and write data.

### 1. Firestore Security Rules (Required)
You must go to the **Firebase Console** > **Firestore Database** > **Rules** tab and paste the following rules. Without these, Firebase will block all attempts to fetch or save property data:

```javascript
rules_version = '2';
service cloud.firestore {
  match /databases/{database}/documents {
    // Allow users to read and write their own profile
    match /users/{userId} {
      allow read, write: if request.auth != null && request.auth.uid == userId;
    }

    // Allow authenticated users to read and write any document 
    // (This is a starting point, you can restrict by userId later)
    match /{collection}/{document} {
      allow read, write: if request.auth != null;
    }

    // Allow users to search for others by email for sharing
    match /users/{userId} {
      allow read: if request.auth != null;
    }
  }
}
```

### 2. Application Code Updates
I have updated `AuthContext.tsx` to ensure the `user` state is populated as the very first action after a successful login, preventing the "Guest User" fallback from appearing.

